AGI -&nbsp;The Israeli forces, which have taken control by the Palestinian side of the Rafah Passage, have completely closed the passage between Egypt and Gaza>, preventing the passage of people and any humanitarian aid: the spokesman of the United Nations Humanitarian Coordination Office, Jens Laerke, while talks in Cairo are still ongoing with the aim of reaching a ceasefire.&nbsp; The Pentagon, for its part, has announced the completion of the work for the construction of an artificial port > which will serve to deliver aid to the Palestinian population
&nbsp;
"Israeli defence forces completely ignore all warnings about what might mean for civilians and humanitarian operations throughout the Gaza Strip," he said. Until now, most of Israel's limited humanitarian assistance granted to the Palestinian enclave since the beginning of the war, last October, entered through the Rafah Pass. Kerem Shalom's secondary vessel, between Gaza and Israel, through which a small volume of humanitarian aid entered last December, was closed again a few days ago by Israel, although the United States assured that it will be reopened in the coming hours.
&nbsp;
"This means that now the two main arteries to bring aid to Gaza are sealed, which makes this morning, when we heard about the situation, one of the darkest of the seven long months of this nightmare," added Laerke. According to UN sources, the Israeli authorities also do not allow UN humanitarian personnel near the border crossing to coordinate the recovery of humanitarian movements. &nbsp;>
<h2> The situation in Rafah</h2>
Israel's tanks entered Rafah in southern Gaza, and Idf took control of the border crossing with Egypt, which, according to the United Nations, closed access to the key humanitarian passage.> Army videos show Israeli tanks taking "operational control" on the Palestinian side of the border crossing, in an explanation that had a "very limited door against very specific objectives".
&nbsp;
The Egyptian government condemned Israeli control over the Palestinian side of the border crossing of Rafah, the only one that is not controlled by Israel and borders Egypt. In a note, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs in Cairo defined the move a "dangerous escalation that threatens the lives of more than a million Palestinians» which depend on this passage as the main means of subsistence, as a safe exit for the wounded and the entry of care for the sick and for the access of humanitarian aid to the Palestinian brothers in Gaza".
&nbsp;
Al Jazeera's correspondent reports that the Israeli army artillery fire hit the local government headquarters in Rafah, as attacks in southern Gaza intensify.
<div </div
&nbsp;
The spokesman of the United Nations Humanitarian Office, Jens Laerke, said that Israel denied access to both Rafah and Kerem Shalom - the other major Gaza vessel for aid, on the border with Israel - with only "one day of fuel available" within the territory besieged. If fuel is not allowed, > "it would be a very effective way to put humanitarian operation in the grave", he warned.<br> Yesterday evening Hamas said he had informed Egypt and Qatar of his "approval of their proposal to cease fire"> in the conflict, pushing the crowd to applaud in the streets of Rafah. The Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office stated that the proposal was "free from the essential demands of Israel", but the government would send negotiators for talks "to exhaust the potential to reach an agreement".
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, he added, "Israel continuing the operation to Rafah to exert military pressure on Hamas in order to advance the release of our hostages and the other objectives of the war." Qatar has declared that today it will send a delegation to Cairo to resume negotiations in the "hope that the talks culminate in reaching an agreement for an immediate and permanent ceasefire in the Strip".<br> The international alarm has grown steadily on the consequences of an Israeli invasion of land in Rafah. The Egyptian Foreign Ministry warned of "gravious humanitarian risks" for over a million civilians fleeing to Rafah and urged Israel to "exercise maximum moderation". Yesterday in a conversation with Netanyahu US President Joe Biden reiterated "his clear position" contrary to an invasion of the city, said the White House.
<h2>Changes of charges
The Egyptian medium 'Al-Qahera News' reported that talks are ongoing in Cairo between delegates of Qatar, Hamas, Egypt and the United States. The Delegation of Qatar and the United States continue their discussions with the Egyptian and Hamas delegation," said the newspaper citing a "high official".
&nbsp;
The talks aim to reach an agreement on the ceasefire in Gaza, a proposal to which Hamas yesterday responded positively. Reports say there are still differences between the positions of Hamas and Israel.
&nbsp;
An Israeli official involved in the hostage liberation negotiations criticized Egypt, Qatar and the United States for their conduct in the talks, claiming that "the mediators acted fully on the Hamas side". The Israeli press writes it citing the public broadcaster Kan. "If there will be no change of approach by the mediators and Hamas, we are on the good road to an expansion of military activities in Rafah," said the official according to Kan, adding that the new counterproposal of Hamas "is a failure for us".
&nbsp;
Hamas spokesman, Osama Hamdan, states that Israel's attack on the Rafah Pass with Egypt is an attempt by Netanyahu to hinder the agreement and implementation of a ceasefire. "The attack of occupation forces at the Rafah Pass is a serious and dangerous crime and escalation against a civil structure that is under the protection of international law," Hamdan said in a press conference in Beirut.<br> "Invading and attacking the Rafah Pass by Israeli forces with Netanyahu's decision is an attempt to hinder the implementation of the agreement to stop the attack against our people. It is a desperate attempt to create a pseudo-victory that can save the face to Netanyahu. This will never be achieved."

