AGI - This week tens of young people have set up pro-Palestinian camps in the universities of Cambridge and Oxford> to protest against the war in the Gaza Strip. According to the British media, about 40 tents were mounted outside King's College, one of the campuses of the University of Cambridge, with banners with the words "Divest now", a reference to the request to end relations with institutions that finance Israel. Meanwhile, the protesters have placed themselves outside the Oxford Natural History Museum, with Palestinian flags draped on the curtains, in those who have called "academies of solidarity for Gaza".
&nbsp;
Undergraduates will be summoned to Downing Street following the growing anger of the government > for their inability to repress anti-Semitic protests. Rishi Sunak> told the cabinet that there was an "unacceptable" increase in anti-Semitism on campus and that ministers will meet the deputy directors to "discuss the need for universities to be safe for our Jewish students". A prime minister spokesman said that Sunak expects university leaders to adopt "strong actions" to address disruptive protests for Palestinians.
&nbsp;
The Cambridge and Oxford sections of the Union of Universities and Colleges (university centers similar to campuses in Britain) expressed their support for camps in a statement. "We ask both universities to act immediately in response to the appeals of staff and students to put an end to investments and collaboration with academic companies or institutions that finance and provide weapons to Israel," they said.
&nbsp;
Since last week, some British universities have set up several pro-Palestinian camps to protest the war in the Gaza Strip. The first was set up at the end of April at the University of Warwick in Coventry, followed by Bristol, Sheffield, Manchester, Leeds and Newcastle, according to the organizers. &nbsp;

